<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Fire may cause mortality in dense stands, with intense fires killing both seeds and plants. <i>Lupinus arboreus </i>can sprout after burning. However, soil-stored seeds, which are long-lived, germinate readily after fire on bare sand. Annual weeds follow due to the nitrogen enrichment of soils by <i>L. arboreus. </i>The higher plant cover can potentially increase frequency and intensity of fires (Pickart and Sawyer 1998, Ross 2002b). Along the Point Reyes Peninsula, <i>L. arboreus </i>increased significantly in overall cover after fire, particularly in areas with less intense fire where soil-stored seeds were more likely to survive and germinate; however, the lupine mostly disappeared within 5 years after the fire (Holzman and Folger 2003).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
