    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ad, Af, Ah-l). Native stands occur on dune areas from San Mateo Co. with <i>Baccharis pilularis</i> to around Monterey Bay (Priestley et al. 2004) and elsewhere south to Morro Bay in San Luis Obispo Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa, Ae, Ah-l). Native stands exist at Sea Ranch on terraces in Sonoma Co. (Hektner and Foin 1977) and south to Point Reyes National Seashore in Marin Co. (Holton and Johnson 1979, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). The blue form of <i>L. arboreus</i> grows at Manchester State Park in Mendocino Co. (Pickart 2000, CNPS unpublished data 2020). Naturalized stands exist from Centerville Beach to Trinidad Head in Humboldt Co. (Duebendorfer 1989, LaBanca 1993, Pickart and Barbour 2007, Parker 1974) and from Point George to the mouth of the Smith River (Pickart 2000) in Del Norte Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-c). Native stands are sporadic near Point Conception and on the Nipomo Dunes. Johnson and Rodriguez (2001) and Junak et al. (2007) report the species for the northern Channel Island in part of an association with <i>L. albifrons.</i></li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Along the northern California coast, habitat restoration is necessary to maintain viable populations of dune mat natives and native lupines. Pickart and Sawyer (1998) and Pickart (2000) review dune mat restoration methods to remove <i>L. arboreus</i>. They found that manual removal of plants, litter, and duff is effective, but removal was labor intensive and expensive if stands are extensive. </div>
</div>

    

    

